latestPosts.caption:
Arthshila Turns 9

23 April 2016 – 23 April 2025

Nine years of shaping stories, building bridges, and creating spaces where ideas breathe.

To everyone who has spoken, sung, painted, screened, walked in, or simply listened—you are Arthshila.

Here’s to the journey behind us, and the imagination ahead.

A Timeline of Togetherness

1️⃣ 2016: Patna became home to an idea called Arthshila.
2️⃣ 2018: Arthshila Studios in Siwan gave it a creative heartbeat.
3️⃣ 2021: Arthshila Ahmedabad joined, sparking a dialogue of design and discourse.
4️⃣ 2022: Arthshila Santiniketan followed, echoing with art and adda.
5️⃣ 2024: Arthshila Delhi and Goa embraced the Arthshila spirit.
6️⃣ 2025: Up Next Patna, this time as our newest centre.

From exhibitions to conversations, residencies to readings—Arthshila is a growing archive of lived culture.

Thank you for walking with us on this journey.

latestPosts.caption:
Something magical unfolded at the Flowing Heritage Exhibition, Arthshila Delhi. We brought the legendary Pabuji ki Phad to life—not just to be seen, but heard.

Through an interactive textile, we immortalised the Art of Phad Vanchan in our own way—letting people listen and experience the story like never before.

Grateful to @anjanasomany for the opportunity to be a part of this beautiful celebration of heritage. It allowed us to create something innovative that we've never done before. Huge thanks to @jsw.foundation and @arthshila_delhi for creating a space where tradition met innovation.

This beautiful Phad is painted by @vijaijosi 

#ArthshilaDelhi
#PhadSamvad
#PabujikiPhad
#Dastangoi
#TraditionmeetsInnovation

A heartfelt thank you to all who joined us for the 𝐏𝐡𝐚𝐝 𝐩𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤𝐬𝐡𝐨𝐩 with Phad Artist 𝐕𝐢𝐣𝐚𝐲 𝐉𝐨𝐬𝐡𝐢, a master from this 700-year-old tradition from Shahpura. Trained by his esteemed father Shantilal Joshi, Vijay shared his expertise with the participants of the workshop. He ably blended ancient techniques with modern perspectives. Each participant was thrilled to take back a piece of painting made on the traditional cloth canvas typically used for such artworks. Overall It was an incredible experience

📍Arthshila Delhi, Pocket B-19/1, Okhla Phase II, New Delhi.

We’re bringing 𝐅𝐥𝐨𝐰𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐇𝐞𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐚𝐠𝐞: 𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐈𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐚𝐧 𝐖𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐍𝐚𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 curated by Anjana Somany (@anjanasomany) to a close with a special evening of storytelling, music, and tradition.

Closing Reception details: 
🗓 Sun, 27th Apr 2025
🕔 5 PM onwards
📍 Arthshila Delhi, Pocket B-19/1, Okhla Phase II, New Delhi

Join us this weekend for a special evening of performances 𝐉𝐮𝐠𝐚𝐥𝐛𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐢: 𝐑𝐞𝐭𝐞𝐥𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐡𝐚𝐝 featuring  Fouzia Dastango (@fouziadastango) and Ritesh Yadav (@rites._.ydv) and 𝐏𝐡𝐚𝐝 𝐁𝐚𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐡𝐧𝐚 𝐨𝐧 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐑𝐚𝐯𝐚𝐧𝐡𝐚𝐭𝐭𝐚 by Bhopa Sugnaram and Bhopi. 

This final celebration marks the close of our multidisciplinary craft and art exhibition exploring India’s deep and timeless connection with water—an elemental force that continues to inspire creativity, culture, and innovation. 

Exhibition on view till 27th April 2025.

Catch it before it leaves!

latestPosts.caption:
We’re wrapping up our exhibition series with a special lineup of events – and this weekend marks the final one!

Join us for the closing workshop 𝐖𝐚𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐒𝐭𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐞𝐬 𝐢𝐧 𝐏𝐚𝐛𝐮𝐣𝐢 𝐤𝐢 𝐏𝐡𝐚𝐝 led by @vijaijosi
Step into the world of Phad Painting a traditional Rajasthani art form that tells stories through vibrant visuals and intricate details. 

𝐃𝐚𝐭𝐞: Sun, 27 Apr 2025 
𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬: 2:30 PM - 4:30 PM
𝐋𝐨𝐜𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧: Arthshila Delhi, Pocket B-19/1, Okhla Phase II, New Delhi

🔗Registration link in bio (no fees required)

All materials will be provided – just bring your curiosity and creative spirit!

About the Artist:
Vijay Joshi is a renowned Phad artist from Shahpura, Rajasthan, celebrated for his dedication to preserving and innovating within this traditional art form. As the 13th-generation practitioner in his family, he learned the nuances of Phad painting under the guidance of his father, Shri Shantilal Joshi, a National Award winner in 1991.

latestPosts.caption:
Join us for a compelling illustrated talk by Orijit Sen as he takes us on a journey through 𝐑𝐢𝐯𝐞𝐫 𝐨𝐟 𝐒𝐭𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐞𝐬, his groundbreaking 1994 graphic novel that emerged at the heart of the Narmada Bachao Andolan.

𝐃𝐚𝐭𝐞: Sat, 26 April 2025
𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠𝐬: 5 PM - 6 PM
𝐋𝐨𝐜𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧: Arthshila Delhi, Pocket B 19/1, Okhla Phase II, New Delhi

About the talk:
An exploration of the philosophical and ideological resistance that informed one of the greatest mass movements in post-independent India. The history of the Narmada Bachao Andolan continues to resonate today and inspire environmental struggles around the world. It interweaves and contrasts the ancient sacred river stories of the people of the Narmada Valley and contemporary stories of the dam(n)ing of the river driven by a mechanistic/materialistic view of water as a mere 'resource' to be exploited for unsustainable goals.
